  "prompt": "In Bhagavad Gita 18th chapter, Lord Krishna says \"Arjuna is his dearest friend\". I am curious to know if there are any stories in Arjuna's previous birth, to become Lord's dearest friend in Vishnu's incarnation as Krishna?",
  "response": "In Hindu mythology, the relationship between Lord Krishna and Arjuna is deeply significant and rooted in both their past lives and the cosmic play (leela) depicted in various texts. While the Bhagavad Gita itself doesn't detail the past lives of Arjuna, there are stories outside of the Gita that provide insights into their eternal bond.\n\nOne such story comes from the Mahabharata and other related Puranic texts, which suggest that Arjuna and Krishna's bond transcends their current incarnations. According to certain legends, in a previous age, Arjuna was the sage Nara, and Krishna was the sage Narayana. Together, they are often referred to as the twin sages, Nara-Narayana, who took human forms to fight against evil and protect dharma (righteousness).\n\nThe Nara-Narayana incarnation signifies the eternal friendship and divine purpose shared by Krishna and Arjuna. As constant companions in their divine mission across various lives, it is believed that this deep connection and purpose make Arjuna especially dear to Krishna.\n\nThese stories emphasize the eternal and cosmic nature of their relationship, illustrating why Arjuna holds a special place as Krishna's dearest friend in the Mahabharata.",
